mprisoned youth are often quite resilient and can be successful at creating lives for themselves after months or even years of living in institutions run by the juvenile justice system. This book narrates the day-to-day experiences of these young men and women, focusing on their attempts to surmount the challenges of adulthood, resisting a return to criminal activity, and formulating long-term goals for a secure adult future.   aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 07. Jan 2021) 0aJustice, Administration ofzCaliforniazLos Angeles. 0aJuvenile delinquentsxRehabilitationzCaliforniazLos Angeles. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh1 aInderbitzin, Michelle1 aInderbitzin, Michelle, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aTerry, Diane, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertRUP eBook-Package 2017z978311066609040uhttps://doi.org/10.36019/978081357449340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780813574493423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780813574493.jpg  a978-3-11-066609-0  RUP eBook-Package 2017b2017  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aEBA_STMALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA12STME  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK